[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626967&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626967&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Roy Smith writes...

&gt;                               It would be convenient to have people on
&gt;the outside simply send to person@phri.nyu.edu and have phri.nyu.edu be a
&gt;nickname for phri.phri.nyu.edu, but I can't seem to figure out any way to
&gt;do that.

We had the same problem.  Our solution was to name a specific machine
fccc.edu and then include a cname record for its old name (ampere.rm.fccc.edu)
to point to that.  We picked a special IP address which would **ALWAYS**
be fccc.edu, and got it in the NIC's host tables.  If we ever "shift our flag",
we intend to renumber the existing fccc.edu to a new number and give the new
"fccc.edu" the number reserved for it.  We found it a lot easier to make
changes internally than to convince the rest of the net outside of the DNS
to do so.

